{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|なんじ}}

{{IPAchar|/namuti/}} → *{{IPAchar|/nandi/}} → {{IPAchar|/nand͡ʑi/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=なんじ|-}}.  Originally derived as a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=なんじ|汝|tr1=na|t1=you|pos=ancient term|貴|tr2=muchi|pos2=honorific suffix}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>

Originally used to refer [[honorifically]] to the [[second person]].  From around the {{w|Nara period}}, the [[honorific]] sense lessened, and the term was used to refer to social [[equal]]s or occasionally social [[inferior]]s.  By the {{w|Muromachi period}}, this term was the most common [[second person]] [[pronoun]] for social [[inferior]]s.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|しか}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=しか|-}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>  Compound of {{compound|ja|sort=しか|し|tr1=shi|t1=that|pos1=demonstrative, likely related to {{m|ja|さ|tr=sa}}, modern {{m|ja|そう|tr=sō}}|か|tr2=ka|pos2=suffix indicating state}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>

The [[interjection]] sense appears to have developed from the [[adverb]] sense.

